# Pear Shaped Pink Diamond Ring: The Complete {{year}} Guide (Lab & Natural, Settings & Prices)

## TL;DR — Key Facts Before You Shop

- **The Pink Multiplier:** A 1.28ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink pear costs $1,820 in lab-grown. A 0.50ct GIA Fancy Intense Pink pear costs $82,386 in natural. Same pear shape, same color category label — the lab-to-natural price gap for pink is 45x, versus 5–8x for colorless diamonds
- **The Intensity Ladder:** GIA pink intensity grades (Fancy Brownish Pink → Fancy Pink → Fancy Intense → Fancy Vivid) multiply value by 2x–33x per step, independent of carat weight. A 0.50ct Fancy Brownish Pink costs $2,524; a 0.50ct Fancy Intense Pink costs $82,386 — same half-carat stone, $79,862 price difference driven entirely by intensity grade
- **Most-reviewed setting for pink:** [Twisted Halo Diamond Engagement Ring in 14k White Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/twisted-halo-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-item-sku-192890?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$1,955 (197 reviews)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/twisted-halo-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-item-sku-192890?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — halo surrounds the pink pear with white diamonds that contrast-amplify perceived saturation
- **Best lab pink entry:** [IGI 1.28ct Fancy Vivid Pink VVS2](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-16551156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$1,820](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-16551156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — Vivid intensity in a certified pear at sub-$2,000 is exclusive to lab-grown
- **Best natural pink entry:** [GIA 0.50ct Fancy Brownish Pink SI1](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28989877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$2,524](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28989877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
- **Metal rule:** Yellow gold for Brownish Pink grades — warm metal amplifies warm pink saturation and allows H–I color savings logic to be redirected toward stone budget. White gold for Purplish Pink and Intense/Vivid grades — cool metal creates maximum color contrast against pure pink
- **Contrarian Truth:** The cheapest natural pink pear diamonds (GIA Fancy Brownish Pink, $2,524) deliver more visible pink saturation per dollar than almost any other gemstone category. Meanwhile, a 3ct+ IGI Fancy Vivid Pink pear at $1,834 outperforms a 0.53ct GIA Fancy Intense Pink at $39,989 on every saturation metric the eye can measure at arm's length. The rarity narrative of natural pink diamonds is real — the optical superiority narrative is not →

---

The pear shaped pink diamond ring is the highest-concentration intersection of two premium categories: pear cut demand and fancy colored diamond rarity. Buyers searching this specific combination have already narrowed both shape and color, making search intent here unusually focused.

The central decision is not which setting to choose — that comes after. The primary buying decision is which pink diamond tier is appropriate: IGI lab-grown Vivid Pink at $1,820–$3,700, GIA natural Fancy Brownish Pink at $2,524–$12,000, natural Orangy or Purplish Pink at $15,000–$55,000, or GIA Fancy Intense/Vivid at $39,000–$213,000+. Each tier is a fundamentally different purchase with different value logic, different setting recommendations, and different GIA terminology to understand.

This guide covers the complete Blue Nile pink pear diamond catalog — 40+ stones across lab and natural, organized by intensity tier — the two frameworks that determine every pink pear buying decision, and the specific pear settings that amplify pink color most effectively at every budget.

---

## The Pink Multiplier: Lab vs. Natural Pink Pear Diamonds

The Pink Multiplier is the ratio between lab-grown and natural pink diamond prices — a gap that is categorically larger for pink than for any other diamond color category.

**Why the gap is 45x, not 5x.** In colorless diamonds, lab-grown typically trades at 80–90% below natural equivalent — a 5–10x multiplier. In pink diamonds, the gap is 30x–80x. A 1.28ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink pear costs $1,820 in lab-grown. A 0.50ct GIA Fancy Intense Pink pear costs $82,386 in natural — and the 0.50ct stone is half the carat weight. The driver is the Argyle mine: when the Rio Tinto Argyle mine in Australia closed in 2020, it ended the source of 90% of the world's natural pink diamonds. Natural pink supply has effectively ceased; lab supply has not.

**What lab Vivid Pink means technically.** IGI certifies lab-grown pink diamonds with the same GIA intensity nomenclature: Fancy Light, Fancy, Fancy Intense, Fancy Vivid. A lab IGI Fancy Vivid Pink VVS2 has been graded with the same color intensity standard as a GIA Fancy Vivid Pink natural — the Vivid saturation is real and certified, not a trade term. The difference is origin and rarity premium, not color performance.

**When the Pink Multiplier favors lab:** Any buyer whose primary goal is maximum pink saturation at minimum spend. A 3.63ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink VVS2 pear at $2,019 delivers more total face-up pink surface area than any natural pink pear in this catalog under $50,000 — by a significant margin. The Pink Multiplier makes the case for lab-grown pink pears mathematically unambiguous for the value-driven buyer.

**When natural wins.** Buyers purchasing for investment, estate value, or the provenance of a post-Argyle natural pink diamond have a legitimate reason to choose natural. The rarity story is real: natural pink diamonds are becoming genuinely scarcer every year. That rarity does not translate to optical superiority at arm's length — it translates to documented scarcity and auction-house value floors.

---

## The Intensity Ladder: How GIA Pink Grades Drive Price

The Intensity Ladder is the single most important framework in pink diamond buying: GIA intensity grade multiplies the value of a pink diamond more aggressively than any other quality factor, including carat weight.

**The GIA pink intensity scale.** GIA grades pink diamond color in ascending intensity: Faint → Very Light → Light → Fancy Light → Fancy → Fancy Brownish/Brownish → Fancy Dark → Fancy Intense → Fancy Vivid → Fancy Deep. The pink pear diamonds on Blue Nile span: Fancy Brownish Pink, Fancy Brown Pink, Fancy Brownish Purplish Pink, Fancy Orangy Pink, Fancy Purplish Pink, Fancy Purple Pink, Fancy Pink, Fancy Intense Pink, Fancy Intense Orangy Pink, Fancy Intense Purple Pink, and Fancy Vivid grades in lab-grown.

**The Intensity Ladder in data.** Using only 0.50ct stones from this catalog: Fancy Brownish Pink SI1 costs $2,524. Fancy Pink VS2 costs $32,441. Fancy Intense Pink SI2 costs $82,386. That is a 33x price increase across the same carat weight — driven purely by the GIA intensity designation. Clarity (SI1 to VS2 to SI2) is essentially irrelevant at this price level; intensity is everything.

**The modifier effect.** GIA intensity modifiers — Brownish, Orangy, Purplish — describe hue contamination. Brownish Pink is the most common modifier and carries the lowest price premium. Purplish Pink (raspberry secondary hue) and Orangy Pink (salmon/coral secondary) carry successively higher premiums because they are more rare in natural production. Fancy Orangy Pink at 0.55ct costs $20,537; Fancy Brownish Pink at the same weight costs $2,524–$6,066. The modifier alone drives an 8x–10x multiple.

**How to use the Intensity Ladder practically.** Buyers who want visible pink color and cannot spend $30,000+ on a natural stone have two options: buy Fancy Brownish Pink natural at $2,524–$12,000 (real GIA-certified pink color, Brownish modifier reduces price) or buy IGI Fancy Vivid lab at $1,820–$3,700 (highest intensity grade, lab origin, no rarity premium). Buyers pursuing pure Fancy or Intense natural pink at $32,000–$82,000 should understand they are buying a rarity tier, not a proportional optical upgrade.

