The two [GIA 0.50ct Fancy Brownish Pink SI1](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28989877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) stones at [$2,524 each](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28989877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) are the most accessible natural GIA pink pear diamonds in this catalog — half-carat, SI1 clarity (eye-clean at this scale), GIA-certified natural pink origin. The Brownish modifier means a warm brownish-pink color rather than pure bubblegum pink; in yellow gold settings the brownish modifier is optically neutralized by the warm metal reflection.

The [GIA 0.51ct Fancy Brownish Purplish Pink CO](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-21641747?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$3,011](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-21641747?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) carries the CO clarity designation — Blue Nile's Collection grade, indicating inclusions visible to the naked eye. For a pink colored diamond where color is the primary value driver, CO clarity is frequently acceptable; the color saturation is certified GIA and the inclusions, though visible, do not interrupt the pink face-up appearance. Always verify via 360° HD video before purchasing any CO clarity stone.

The price jump from [$3,300](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-29217351?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (Fancy Brownish Pink SI2) to [$5,947](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-24950960?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (Fancy Brown Pink SI2) at the same 0.50ct represents the "Brownish" versus "Brown" modifier distinction — Brown Pink has stronger brown contamination than Brownish Pink, yet prices more than Brownish. This reflects supply variability, not a systematic rule: individual pink stone pricing depends heavily on the specific GIA certificate.

