The [GIA 0.50ct Fancy Pink VS2](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-22631590?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$32,441](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-22631590?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the first stone in this catalog with no modifier — pure "Fancy Pink" on the GIA certificate. That modifier absence is what costs $30,000 more than a half-carat Brownish Pink at $2,524: pure Fancy Pink means no brown, no orange, no purple contamination, just pink. At 0.50ct the stone is small; the rarity premium is entirely in the color purity.

The [GIA 0.53ct Fancy Intense Pink SI2](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-16957313?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$39,989](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-16957313?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) introduces the Intense grade — one step below Vivid, two steps above Fancy. A half-carat Fancy Intense Pink natural pear is among the rarest commercial pear diamonds in existence. This stone is a rarity purchase; at $39,989 the buyer is acquiring documented scarcity more than proportionally improved color appearance.

The [GIA 1.24ct Fancy Brownish Pink IF](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-27272384?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$32,671](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-27272384?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) represents IF (Internally Flawless) clarity on a Brownish Pink — the inverse of the usual pink diamond priority hierarchy. Flawless clarity in a Brownish Pink modifier creates an unusual price: $32,671 despite the Brownish modifier, driven by the IF premium in a stone where clarity is secondary to color. This is a collector configuration, not an optimal optical-value purchase.

