## Metal Choice for a Pink Pear Diamond Ring

Metal choice for a pink pear ring is determined by GIA intensity grade and the modifier on the stone's certificate, not by personal preference alone.

| Pink Grade | Correct Metal | Why | Setting Recommendation |
|-----------|--------------|-----|----------------------|
| Fancy Brownish Pink | Yellow Gold | Warm metal neutralizes brownish modifier, reads closer to pure pink | Hand-Engraved Micropavé YG ($1,600 / 87 reviews) |
| Fancy Brown Pink | Yellow Gold or Rose Gold | Maximum warm reflection suppresses brown secondary | Milgrain V-Shank YG ($1,790 / 32 reviews) |
| Fancy Purplish Pink | White Gold | Cool metal amplifies purple-pink contrast | Scalloped Pavé WG ($1,970 / 164 reviews) |
| Fancy Orangy Pink | White Gold | Cool metal creates coral/salmon contrast; warm metal muddies orange | Twisted Halo WG ($1,955 / 197 reviews) |
| Fancy Pink (no modifier) | White Gold | Maximum contrast against pure pink saturation | French Pavé Crown WG ($2,520 / 87 reviews) |
| Fancy Intense / Vivid | White Gold or Platinum | Highest intensity reads most dramatically against cool metal | Graduated Diamond Halo JA WG ($2,985 / 99 reviews) |
| Lab IGI Vivid Pink | Either — white for contrast, yellow for warmth | Lab vivid saturation is intense enough to read in both metals | Twisted Halo WG (197 reviews) or Interlaced Halo YG ($1,750 / 29 reviews) |

**The rose gold exception.** Rose gold works for lab-grown Vivid Pink pear diamonds where the buyer wants maximum warmth and a monochromatic pink-on-pink aesthetic — pink stone, rose gold setting. This reads as a fashion statement more than a color-amplification strategy. For natural Brownish Pink where color amplification is the goal, yellow gold outperforms rose gold because 14k yellow gold contains more yellow than 14k rose gold's copper-dominant alloy. For full rose gold pear analysis, see the **[rose gold pear diamond ring guide](/rose-gold-pear-diamond-ring)**.

---

## Clarity and Cut for a Pink Pear Diamond Ring

Clarity in pink diamonds is evaluated differently than in colorless diamonds. GIA and IGI both apply the same clarity grades (FL, IF, VVS1/2, VS1/2, SI1/2, I1/2) to pink stones, but the commercial emphasis is on color saturation — not clarity. Most pink diamond buyers accept SI1–SI2 clarity in exchange for better color grade, and this is the correct priority hierarchy at every budget.

**The SI2 acceptability rule.** At 0.50ct–0.60ct, SI2 inclusions in a pear diamond are often not visible to the naked eye without magnification, particularly when the stone is set in a halo that partially covers the inclusion zone. The majority of natural Orangy Pink, Purplish Pink, and Intense Pink stones in this catalog carry SI2 clarity — because SI2 is the most common clarity tier at which sellers can achieve premium pink intensity grades without the additional rarity cost of VS or VVS clarity.

**The CO clarity note.** Two stones in this catalog carry CO (Collection) clarity — Blue Nile's grade below SI2. These stones have visible inclusions. For pink diamonds specifically, if the color grade (Brownish Purplish Pink, Brown Pink) is the primary purchase driver, CO clarity may deliver better pink saturation per dollar than a VS1 Brownish Pink at double the price. Always verify CO stones via 360° HD video. Full pear clarity guidance in the **[pear cut diamond guide](/pear-cut-diamond)**.

**Bow-tie in pink pears.** Pear diamonds can exhibit a bow-tie shadow across the center. In pink pear diamonds, the bow-tie presents as a darker area within the pink — it does not change color, it reduces saturation locally. A Fancy Vivid Pink pear with a strong bow-tie may read closer to Fancy Intense Pink in the bow-tie zone. Halo settings partially obscure mild bow-tie presence. Always verify pink pear diamonds via 360° video specifically for bow-tie severity before purchasing.

