## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is a pear shaped pink diamond ring?

A pear shaped pink diamond ring features a pear-cut (teardrop) diamond in a pink color grade — either lab-grown IGI Fancy Intense or Vivid Pink, or natural GIA Fancy Pink through Fancy Vivid. The pear shape is the most popular non-round silhouette for fancy colored diamonds because the elongated outline maximizes face-up color presentation. Pink pear diamonds are available in natural (GIA certified, $2,524–$1,865,681) and lab-grown (IGI certified, $1,820–$3,728) with significantly different price structures.

### What is the Pink Multiplier?

The Pink Multiplier is the price ratio between lab-grown and natural pink pear diamonds — approximately 30x–80x, versus the 5–8x gap in colorless diamonds. A 3ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink pear costs $1,834 in lab-grown; a 0.50ct GIA Fancy Intense Pink costs $82,386 in natural. The gap exists because natural pink diamonds formed in conditions that essentially no longer exist commercially after the 2020 Argyle mine closure, making them structurally non-reproducible at scale.

### What is the Intensity Ladder for pink diamonds?

The Intensity Ladder is the GIA intensity grading progression for pink diamonds: Fancy Brownish Pink → Fancy Pink → Fancy Intense → Fancy Vivid. Each step up multiplies value by 2x–10x or more, independent of carat weight. In this catalog: Fancy Brownish Pink SI1 at 0.50ct costs $2,524; Fancy Intense Pink SI2 at 0.53ct costs $39,989; Fancy Intense Pink SI2 at 0.50ct costs $82,386. Carat weight alone does not explain these differences — intensity grade does.

### Which setting is best for a pink pear diamond?

Halo settings in white gold provide the strongest color amplification for pink pear diamonds. The Twisted Halo in 14k White Gold ($1,955 / 197 reviews) is the most-reviewed and most-validated option. White diamonds surrounding the pink center create a contrast boundary that makes the pink saturation appear more intense. For Brownish Pink natural stones, yellow gold settings — particularly the Hand-Engraved Micropavé ($1,600 / 87 reviews) — suppress the brownish modifier through warm metal reflection.

### Is yellow gold or white gold better for a pink pear diamond?

Yellow gold is correct for GIA Fancy Brownish Pink and Fancy Brown Pink stones — warm metal reflection neutralizes the brownish modifier, making the pink read closer to pure pink at the same intensity grade. White gold is correct for GIA Fancy Purplish Pink, Fancy Orangy Pink, Fancy Pink (no modifier), and all Intense or Vivid grades — the cool metal creates maximum color contrast that amplifies the pure pink or colored-modifier hue. Lab-grown IGI Vivid Pink pears work in both metals; white gold creates contrast, yellow gold creates warmth.

### What is a CO clarity pink diamond?

CO is Blue Nile's Collection clarity designation — below SI2, with inclusions visible to the naked eye. Two stones in this catalog carry CO clarity: a [0.51ct Fancy Brownish Purplish Pink at $3,011](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-21641747?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and a [1.00ct Fancy Brown Pink at $11,566](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-21641754?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). In colored diamonds where color is the primary value factor, CO clarity can be acceptable if the color saturation is certified and verified. Always view CO stones via 360° HD video before purchasing.

### Are natural pink pear diamonds a good investment?

Post-Argyle natural pink diamonds (after the 2020 mine closure) have structural supply constraints that support long-term value floors. No new significant natural pink diamond source has replaced Argyle production. Buyers purchasing natural GIA pink pear diamonds above $30,000 are acquiring objects that will likely not become more abundant — the rarity is structural, not speculative. Investment value is most defensible in higher intensity grades (Fancy Intense, Vivid) and pure grades (no Brownish modifier) where rarity is most documented.

### What carat weight should I choose for a pink pear diamond?

In natural pink, 0.50ct is the most accessible weight where full GIA certification and meaningful face-up pink saturation intersect — the two $2,524 Brownish Pink SI1 stones are the entry point. At 1ct+ in natural pink, prices jump to $10,000–$12,000+ for Brownish grades — 1ct natural pink pears are genuinely rare post-Argyle objects. In lab-grown, carat weight is less constrained by budget: 3ct+ IGI Vivid Pink pears are available under $2,100. Buy as much carat weight as the budget allows in lab-grown; in natural, buy as much intensity grade as the budget allows.

### Do pink pear diamonds show a bow-tie effect?

Yes — pear diamonds can show a bow-tie (darkened butterfly-shaped shadow across the center) and this is present in pink pears as it is in colorless pears. In pink stones, the bow-tie appears as a darker, less-saturated zone within the pink face-up. Halo settings partially reduce the visible impact of mild bow-ties by surrounding the stone with reflective accent diamonds. Always verify any pink pear diamond via 360° HD video before purchasing, with specific attention to bow-tie severity in the center of the stone. Full bow-tie analysis in the **[pear cut diamond guide](/pear-cut-diamond)**.

### What is the difference between Fancy Pink and Fancy Intense Pink?

Fancy Pink is GIA's base pink intensity designation with no hue modifier — pure pink saturation at the Fancy grade. Fancy Intense Pink is one grade higher on the intensity scale: deeper saturation, stronger color presence, more vivid appearance. In this catalog, the price difference between these two grades at half-carat weight is: Fancy Pink VS2 at $32,441 versus Fancy Intense Pink SI2 at $39,989–$82,386. The Intense designation can double the value of an otherwise comparable stone.

### What is the cheapest natural pink pear diamond on Blue Nile?

The most affordable natural GIA pink pear diamonds in this catalog are two [GIA 0.50ct Fancy Brownish Pink SI1](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28989877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) stones at [$2,524 each](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28989877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). These carry the Brownish modifier (warm brownish-pink, not pure pink) and SI1 clarity (eye-clean at 0.50ct scale). In a yellow gold setting, the brownish modifier reads closer to pure warm pink. Combined with the Hand-Engraved Micropavé YG at $1,600, the total ring is approximately $4,124 — the most affordable natural GIA pink pear ring in this catalog.

### How does the pear shape work with pink diamonds?

The pear shape maximizes face-up color area in a colored diamond by presenting the stone's largest flat surface at maximum viewing angle. The elongated oval-with-point silhouette creates more face-up surface area per carat than a round brilliant or princess cut of equivalent weight, which increases visible pink saturation. The pear's tapered tip also allows mounting orientation choices — tip up (conventional) or east-west — that affect how the pink color spreads across the finger. Full pear shape analysis in the **[pear cut diamond buying guide](/pear-cut-diamond)** and **[pear shaped diamond ring guide](/pear-shaped-diamond-ring)**.

